<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="1489" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1489">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/294.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 161.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-30">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 30, 1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose herewith a
                            copy and translation of a Presidential decree,<note n="1" xml:id="d1489fn1">Not printed.</note> which was subsequently
                            ratified by the Assembly, approving the transaction entered into by
                            Messers Brown Bros, and Co. and J. and W. Seligman and Co., as
                            authorized agents of the Republic of Nicaragua with the Ethelburga
                            Syndicate Ltd, <pb facs="1198" n="1082" xml:id="pg_1082"/> of London.
                            This decree bears date of the 14th instant, and was published in the
                            “Gaceta Oficial” on the 23rd instant.</p>
                        <p>The President and other members of his Government have expressed to me
                            their gratification at this prompt and satisfactory solution of this
                            harassing and disturbing obligation.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">F. M. Gunther.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>